4. Predictive Utility as a Sufficient Statistic (The "Dark Matter" Corollary)

The Flatness Lemma suggests that the model can encode $G$. The following condition addresses why it might permanently allocate non-zero parameter volume to $G$ despite its low empirical frequency.

Corollary 4.1 (Predictive Utility Threshold).
Let $G$ be the generative grammar of the rare signal $x_{\text{rare}}$. Define the restricted optimum:
\theta_{-G} := \arg\min_{\theta' : \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} \theta' = 0} \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}(\theta')


where $\mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}$ is the population loss over the full web distribution $P_{\text{web}}$ (not merely the pretraining corpus), and $\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G}$ is the projector onto the $G$-subspace. If there exists a marginal improvement $\delta > 0$ such that:
\mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}(\theta) \leq \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}(\theta_{-G}) - \delta


then the $G$-subspace is hypothesized to receive a persistent gradient signal from the aggregate gravitational pull of trillions of common tokens. One can formalize this via the utility gradient flow: the projection of $\nabla \mathcal{L}_{\text{web}}$ onto $\mathcal{M}_G$ yields a restoring force proportional to $\delta$.

Important Clarification on Falsifiability. The condition $\delta > 0$ is an empirical claim, not a tautology. In principle, one could estimate $\delta$ via ablation studies on smaller-scale models (though full-scale counterfactuals at $10^{13}$ parameters are prohibitive). The framework predicts that grammars with measurable utility on common tasks will be preserved; those without will decay. This is testable: if a rare grammar $G$ is observed to persist, the theory implies it must offer some marginal predictive benefit on $P_{\text{web}}$. Conversely, if a grammar is shown to have $\delta \leq 0$ yet still persists, the theory would be challenged. We acknowledge the risk of post-hoc circularity (inferring $\delta > 0$ from observed persistence) and emphasize that Prediction 2 is designed to break this circularity by testing compositional generalization directly.

Intuition: The model does not care about $x_{\text{rare}}$ per se. It cares that knowing $G$ makes it slightly better at predicting the rest of the internet (e.g., using the logic of state transitions to improve next-word prediction in a cooking recipe). This tiny, ubiquitous gradient may prevent the $G$-subspace from collapsing under weight decay or SGD noise.

Remark on Kolmogorov Complexity. Throughout this work, we use Kolmogorov complexity as an idealized proxy for minimum description length (MDL). We acknowledge that Kolmogorov complexity is uncomputable; it serves here as a conceptual tool to capture the intuition that mathematically rigorous structures possess short effective descriptions relative to their predictive power. The framework does not require computing it in practice.

