6. Emergent "Invention": Latent Recombination in Orthogonal Bases

Once isolated manifolds $\mathcal{M}_{G_1}$ and $\mathcal{M}_{G_2}$ are established, the model may synthesize novel concepts via linear operations in the decoupled latent space.

Proposition 6.1 (Linear Superposition in Decoupled Latent Space).
Given two distinct grammars $G_1$ and $G_2$ with decoupled subspaces (i.e., $\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_{G_1}} F(\theta) \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_{G_2}} \approx 0$), and assuming a representation layer where the linear representation hypothesis holds (e.g., the residual stream of a transformer), the model can generate valid outputs corresponding to a new concept by vector addition:
z_{\text{new}} = \alpha \cdot \Pi_{G_1}(z) + \beta \cdot \Pi_{G_2}(z)


where $\Pi_{G_i}$ denotes projection onto the grammar-specific feature subspace. Because the interference term is negligible, the resulting point $z_{\text{new}}$ is not a blurry average but a linear superposition of the features of $G_1$ and $G_2$. The logical behavior of the model on this combined representation may appear as if the two conceptual axes are independently controllable—a phenomenon we term Cartesian Recombination. This corresponds to a point in the data distribution that is logically valid yet historically empty (never seen in training).

Example.
Suppose the model has learned a dedicated FSA Subspace and a dedicated Control Theory Subspace. The recombined vector $z_{\text{new}}$ corresponds to "Control of Finite State Automata." This exact phrase may never appear in the training corpus, yet the model may generate it coherently because the underlying mathematics decouples and recombines cleanly.

