11. Conclusion

We have presented a geometric framework for understanding how ultra-large models might preserve and control rare, logically coherent signals across both pretraining and post-training alignment. The framework proposes that mathematically rigorous, low-frequency concepts survive not by chance but as attractor states in the loss landscape, stabilized by compression efficiency and marginal predictive utility. We offered a scaling heuristic for the decoupling rate of distinct logical manifolds as $\mathcal{O}(\sqrt{\text{eff}(P)}/\sqrt{D})$ and unified the phenomena of decoupling and flatness through the alignment of the Fisher Information Matrix and the Hessian.

We further argued that post-training alignment poses a distinct threat to these structures, requiring explicit geometric constraints to prevent subspace collapse or drift. The proposed Projection-Corrected Alignment offers a principled path toward retaining deep, niche knowledge while shaping model behavior. We have been explicit about the assumptions, heuristics, and measurement challenges underlying the framework, and we have articulated falsifiable empirical predictions to guide future investigation.

As models continue to scale, the ability to navigate and control their internal geometry may become as critical as optimizing scalar loss functions. The rare may remain accessible—if we build the tools to identify and preserve the subspaces where structured knowledge resides.

