12. Empirical Predictions

To ensure the framework is falsifiable and empirically grounded, we articulate four concrete predictions that distinguish this geometric account from alternative narratives of scaling and alignment. We also note the practical estimation strategies that can be employed to test them.

Prediction 1: FIM Sparsity Transition.
As a function of the ratio $D / \text{eff}(P_{\text{data}})$, the off-diagonal Frobenius norm $\|\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i} F(\theta) \mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_j}\|_F$ should decay approximately as $1/\sqrt{D}$ for $D \gg \text{eff}(P)$. In practice, the projectors $\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_i}$ can be approximated by performing PCA on concept-specific activation vectors (e.g., activations for prompts about "FSA" vs. "Control Theory"). The empirical Fisher (or Hessian) can be approximated via gradient outer products on a representative sample. A transition from dense to block-diagonal structure should be observable as parameter count increases beyond the effective data rank. This prediction directly tests the decoupling heuristic (Lemma 2.5).

Prediction 2: Memorization-to-Compression Phase Change.
For a fixed rare signal $x_{\text{rare}}$ governed by a generative grammar $G$, small models (below the hypothesized decoupling threshold) should exhibit pure memorization: they can reproduce $x_{\text{rare}}$ verbatim but fail on held-out samples from $G$. Large models (above the threshold) should exhibit compositional generalization, correctly answering novel queries that require applying $G$. This transition should correlate with the FIM sparsity transition from Prediction 1, distinguishing this account from generic "emergent ability" claims.

Prediction 3: Alignment Damage Curve.
Measuring the projection norm $\|\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} \theta\|$ as a function of alignment steps (e.g., RLHF or instruction tuning) should reveal one of two regimes. If alignment gradients are approximately orthogonal to $\mathcal{M}_G$ (either naturally or via projection constraints), the norm should plateau at a non-zero value, indicating stability. If alignment gradients have significant projection onto $\mathcal{M}_G$, the norm should decay toward zero, indicating subspace collapse. A plot of $\|\mathcal{P}_{\mathcal{M}_G} \theta(t)\|^2$ vs. RLHF step $t$ provides a direct test of the Lyapunov stability argument (Theorem 10.1).

Prediction 4: Recombination Validity.
For any pair of decoupled grammars $G_1, G_2$ identified via approximate FIM block structure, the model should be able to generate coherent, logically consistent outputs for the combined concept $G_1 \wedge G_2$, even when zero training examples of the combination exist. Logical consistency can be evaluated by human experts or automated theorem provers (for formal domains). In contrast, models below the decoupling threshold should produce incoherent or contradictory outputs for the same prompts. This prediction operationalizes Proposition 6.1.

Practical Takeaways for Practitioners.

· Monitor approximate FIM sparsity across model scales to probe the decoupling transition.
· Track projection norms of known knowledge subspaces during RLHF to detect alignment-induced damage.
· Consider projection-corrected updates as a lightweight safety mechanism to preserve valuable latent structures during fine-tuning.

These predictions are amenable to empirical investigation using open-source models across a range of scales, synthetic data with known generative grammars, and controlled post-training interventions. Confirmation of these predictions would provide strong support for the geometric framework; falsification would indicate the need for alternative or revised explanatory accounts.

